Introduction

In this project, I would like ot uncover how the variety of coffee changes the tasting qualities. Coffee varieties are specific typeslike Granny Smith apples or Golden Retriever dogs. Beyond flavor, the variety also influences factors import to growers, such as disease resistance, yield, difficulty of growing, etc. It's clear to many that different regions of the world have unique flavors, such as fruity flavors from Ethiopia or chocolately flavors from Brazil. Less people, including myself, however, understand the varietal's role in the final cup. I'll explore the data to gain a more complete understanding of this unique aspect of coffee.

I will be analyzing coffee metrics using K-means clustering to uncover patterns in the data. I found this data on DataCrayon.com in an article exploring the connections between variety and country of origin. The author of the article forked the dataset from Github, which was originally web scraped from the Coffee Quality Institute website. The data contains features with a variety of different aspects of coffee beans, including owner, country of origin, varietal, taste metrics, among others.

K-means clustering is a common type of unsupervised learning algorithm. It finds clusters in data using centroid-based clustering. The algorithm includes the following steps:

  1. Choose initial randomly chosen centroids.
  2. Assign each point to the nearest centroid.
  3. Recalculate the centroids as means of the points in each cluster.
  4. Repeat this process until the centroids do not change after recalculation.

Because centroids are randomly chosen, your k value is essential to the efficacy of the model. To find an optimal k value that neither generalizes nor overfits the data, the elbow method is used, in which k is plotted against within-cluster sum of squares. Where the graph begins to level off, or forms an 'elbow', is likely your optimal k value.

My key questions I would like to answer in this project are:

  • What are the key differences between the different varieties of coffee?

  • What are the metrics most important to determining variety specific qualities

  • How might these difference impact the consumer and producer?

Visualization

The different qualities of each coffee, like aroma and sweetness, are measured on a scale from 1-10. According to the Specialty Coffee Association, these scores are based on quality of the metric, rather than preference or strength. Let's first plot the different metrics to see if we can find any preliminary patterns.

In[7]:
quality_cols = ['Aroma', 'Flavor', 'Aftertaste', 'Acidity', 'Body', 'Balance', 'Sweetness']
sns.pairplot(df[quality_cols], diag_kind='kde')
plt.suptitle("Pairplot of Coffee Quality Metrics", y=1.02)
plt.show()

Since the data does not appear to be highly separable, it may be difficult to see variety specific patterns. This is somewhat expected as variety is only one of the several different factors, like processing, origin, and roast, that go into the final flavor of a cup. To find patterns in the data, I will use PCA to group the data. I'll remove several outliers as k-means is highly influenced by outliers, and they also more likely represent flawed production processes rather than overall trends in varietal. I'm not quite sure what separates an aroma of 8.65 from an 8.66, but I'll leave that to the pros!

In[9]:
condition_1 = (df['Variety'] == 'Caturra') & (df['Aroma'] == 0) 
condition_2 = (df['Variety'] == 'Caturra') & (df['Aroma'] == 5.08)
condition_3 = (df['Variety'] == 'Caturra') & (df['Acidity'] == 5.25)
condition_4 = (df['Variety'] == 'Unknown') & (df['Body'] == 5.25)
condition_5 = (df['Variety'] == 'Catuai') & (df['Sweetness'] == 1.33)

combined_conditions = condition_1 | condition_2 | condition_3 | condition_4 | condition_5
df= df[~combined_conditions]

Surprisingly, 92% (1218/1311) of the coffees were rated as 10/10 on sweetness. Most tasting metrics all seem to be highly correlated with each other, and center around similar values, except for sweetness. This could be due to the current trend of a greater emphasis on sweet, origin-specific flavors rather than bold, bitter flavors. Another possibility is that it is much easier to produce coffee with totally satisfactory sweetness than other metrics. Sweetness will be more influential than clustering because it's rated so much higher, so I'll remove it. Sweetness is a very important component to coffee, but since almost all coffees scored very highly on sweeetness, our analysis will be more effective only using the other metrics.

Modeling

In[14]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler 
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

X = df[quality_cols]

# Scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

#  Determining optimal k using Elbow Method
inertias = []
silhouette_scores = []
K_range = range(2, 11)

for k in K_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

# Plotting different k values
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(K_range, inertias, 'bo-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within-cluster sum of squares')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal k')
plt.grid(True)

k = 3
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
df['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
scatter = plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=df['cluster'], cmap='viridis', alpha=0.6)
plt.xlabel(f'PC1 ({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]:.2%} variance)')
plt.ylabel(f'PC2 ({pca.explained_variance_ratio_[1]:.2%} variance)')
plt.title('Clusters Visualized in PCA Space')
plt.colorbar(scatter, label='Cluster')
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('clustering_analysis.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Clustering Analysis

The K-Means model identified three clusters, with low, medium and high quality. A clear winner from this analysis is Ethiopian Yirgacheffe one of two coffees with 100% grouping in one cluster, with a mean aroma of 8.12. However, this is actually not a variety. Yirgacheffe is a region in Ethiopia, and is likely an heirloom (indigenous) variety. Actually, a few different of the 'varieties' are mislabelled, such as Hawaiian Kona and Sulawesi. While mislabeled, this actually represents a trend in the coffee market, as people purchase coffee based on a variety of different aspects, not simply just variety. In addition, the region can tell you just as much, if not more, about the quality profile of a coffee than the variety.

Cluster 0 represents 23% (302 observations) of the data, and contains the highest concentrations of varietals such as SL14, SL28, and Sumatra Lington. Cluster 1 respresents the lowest quality in this dataset, with the lowest mean metric out of the entire set, with a mean aftertaste of 6.97. Cluster 0 represents a medium quality.

Impact

My intention with this project is to educate myself as well as the viewer of the different qualities of various coffees.

A few major limitations in this project are present. Firstly, the standard tasting protocol for these coffees includes roasting each coffee to a very light level. This highlights the coffee specific qualities, but inherently favors coffees that perform well at a light roast, such as Ethiopian coffee. For many people, they prefer dark, rich espresso meant to be mixed into a drink with milk and other flavorings. In this case, some coffees that perform poorly on the cupping tests may actually taste much better in practice than other higher rated coffees.
